<table 2 header nowrap>
    <cell>Function</cell><cell>Description</cell>
    <cell><logiccolor>clear</logiccolor></cell><cell>Clears the Case object's contents.</cell>
    <cell><logiccolor>load</logiccolor></cell><cell>Reads a file and stores its contents to a Case object.</cell>
    <cell><logiccolor>open</logiccolor></cell><cell>complete this if used.</cell>
    <cell><logiccolor>read</logiccolor></cell><cell>complete this if used.</cell>
    <cell><logiccolor>save</logiccolor></cell><cell>Writes the contents of the case object to a <font red>file (smg: a file, or a csdb file?)</font>.</cell>
    <cell><logiccolor>view</logiccolor></cell><cell>Displays the contents of the file held by the Case object.</cell>
    <cell><logiccolor>write</logiccolor></cell><cell>complete this if used.</cell>
</table>

In addition to these object functions, Case objects can be used as arguments to the <logiccolor>filename</logiccolor> and <logiccolor>view</logiccolor> functions.


<subheader>Assignments</subheader>

Case objects can be assigned to other Case objects, which will replace the Case's contents with the contents from the assigned Case object.

<logicsyntax>
<arg>case_name</arg> = <arg>another_case_name</arg>;
</logicsyntax>

When a case is used as an argument to a <link user_defined_functions.csdoc>user-defined function</link>, it is <link function_arguments_ref.csdoc>passed by reference</link>. <font red>smg: true?</font>

